
[1]empower

   EMPOW'ER, v.t. [from en or in and power.]

   1. To give legal or moral power or authority to; to authorize, either
   by law, commission, letter of attorney, natural right, or by verbal
   license. The supreme court is empowered to try and decide all cases,
   civil or criminal. The attorney is empowered to sign an acquittance and
   discharge the debtor.

   2. To give physical power or force; to enable. [In this sense the use
   is not frequent,and perhaps not used at all.]
